In a speech delivered at Miami Dade College, National Security Advisor John Bolton outlined the Trump administration's policy towards Cuba, Venezuela, and Nicaragua. Bolton emphasized that the United States will no longer appease dictators and despots near its shores. He condemned the oppressive regimes in these countries and expressed support for the Cuban people's aspirations for real democratic change. Bolton also called for the release of political prisoners, acceptance of international humanitarian assistance, free and fair elections, and the restoration of democratic institutions and the rule of law in Venezuela. He announced that President Trump has signed an executive order imposing tough new sanctions against Venezuela, targeting networks operating within corrupt sectors of its economy. Bolton also condemned the violence and repression carried out by the Ortega regime in Nicaragua and called for the holding of free and fair elections in the country. He emphasized that the United States stands with the people of these countries against oppression, totalitarianism, and domination.